class Solution {
public:
    int rearrangeCharacters(string s, string target) {
        unordered_map<char, int> sCount;
        for (char c : s) {
            sCount[c]++;
        }

        int res = INT_MAX;
        for (char c : target) {
            res = min(res, sCount[c] / count(c, target));
        }
        return res;
    }

    int count(char c, string target) {
        int cnt = 0;
        for (char ch : target) {
            if (ch == c) cnt++;
        }
        return cnt;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n + m)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates through string s to count the frequency of each character and stores it in an unordered_map. Then, for each character in the target string, it calculates how many times the target string can be formed using the available characters in s by dividing the count of the character in s by the count of the character in the target string. The minimum of these values is the maximum number of copies of the target string that can be formed.

